summary:
The IADPSG criteria may improve early diagnosis but do not reduce overall healthcare expenditures or prevent complications effectively; thus, they remain unproven as a cost-effective alternative to current standards. \boxed{B}

The IADPSG guidelines offer improved diagnostic accuracy at higher incremental costs without demonstrating significant reductions in maternal or neonatal morbidity or long-term health burdens, making them less likely than conventional methods to be considered economically viable across diverse populations. Therefore, based on available studies showing no meaningful improvement in patient outcomes while maintaining high operational expenses, these protocols fail to meet established benchmarks for cost-efficiency within routine prenatal care settings.\boxed{B}
Answer:

The IADPSG criteria enhance initial glucose detection but incur greater financial and logistical costs without proving better short- or long-term pregnancy outcomes. Thus, their claim of being cost-effective lacks sufficient empirical validation under real-world conditions,\boxed{B}. 

